<h1 class="hero-h">How to Use Claude as an Engineering Manager <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">The role most undermined by hands-off AI usage.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Engineering managers are caught between technical leadership and people management — both of which AI can amplify, but only with discipline. Here's the daily workflow that lets EMs scale their team's leverage without losing the human-management work that's still their primary job.</p>
<div class="tldr"><div class="tldr-l">Short answer</div><p class="tldr-p">Top EM Claude workflows: 1:1 note synthesis, code review augmentation (not replacement), hiring loop debriefs, exec communication drafting, sprint retro synthesis, technical doc review. Build 5-6 Projects. Frees ~6-8 hours per week for the human work that AI cannot do.</p></div>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Daily EM workflows</h2><h3 class="h3">1. 1:1 notes synthesis</h3><p class="body">After 1:1s, dump raw notes into a Project. Get structured synthesis: themes across the report's recent work, growth areas, recurring blockers, action items. Builds longitudinal view across reports over time.</p><h3 class="h3">2. Code review augmentation</h3><p class="body">Before reviewing a PR yourself, optionally run it through a Code Review Project for first-pass review against your team's style guide, common bug patterns, and architecture principles. Don't replace your review; add to it.</p><h3 class="h3">3. Hiring loop debrief synthesis</h3><p class="body">Multiple interviewers contribute notes; Claude synthesizes into a structured recommendation covering signal across interviews, areas of disagreement, recommended next step.</p><h3 class="h3">4. Up-and-out communications</h3><p class="body">Drafts of weekly updates to your manager, exec team, or product partners. Frame technical work for non-technical audiences. Major time saver.</p><h3 class="h3">5. Sprint retro synthesis</h3><p class="body">Convert retro notes into themes + decisions + actions. Helps the team see patterns it might miss in the moment.</p><h3 class="h3">6. Technical doc / design review</h3><p class="body">Read long design docs and produce structured questions or concerns before the design review meeting. Better-prepared review; less time lost.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">What to keep human</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>The actual 1:1.</strong> Be present. Don't type AI summaries while the report is talking.</li><li><strong>Performance feedback.</strong> AI synthesizes; you decide and deliver.</li><li><strong>The judgment call on a hire.</strong> AI synthesizes interview feedback; you make the call.</li><li><strong>Difficult conversations.</strong> Performance issues, conflict, departures — keep these human.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Common EM AI mistakes</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Using Claude to draft performance reviews.</strong> Wrong. AI synthesizes inputs; you write the review.</li><li><strong>Replacing your code review with AI's.</strong> Wrong. AI catches additional issues; you still substantively review.</li><li><strong>Auto-generating 1:1 agendas without context.</strong> Generic prompts produce generic agendas your reports notice and disengage from.</li><li><strong>Not modeling AI use to your team.</strong> EMs who don't visibly use AI signal that it's not safe for the team to either.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">How to roll out across an engineering team</h2><ol class="ol"><li>EM uses Claude personally for 30 days. Builds fluency.</li><li>Set up shared engineering Projects (code review, design review, doc gen).</li><li>Senior engineers adopt next; provide structured workflows.</li><li>Junior engineers adopt with explicit guidance — don't let AI substitute for skill development.</li><li>Measure: PR throughput, time-to-merge, defect rate, EM 1:1 cadence quality. Adjust based on what you see.</li></ol></div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">FAQ</h2>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Can AI replace 1:1s?</h3><p class="faq-qa">No. The presence and listening matter. AI summarizes after, doesn't substitute during.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should I use AI in performance review writing?</h3><p class="faq-qa">For synthesis of context — yes. For writing the review — no. The judgment must be yours.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Will AI replace engineering managers?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Very unlikely in the foreseeable future. The role is primarily relationship and judgment, which AI doesn't do well.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">How does AI change what engineers report into me?</h3><p class="faq-qa">More leverage per engineer. Often higher quality output per IC. The EM job stays human.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should I hire fewer EMs because of AI?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Probably not. Span of control limits are about human attention, not productivity per IC.</p></div>
</div></section>

